## Mormyrids
- Introduction
	- This paper will discuss mormyrids, a species of weakly-electric fish with extremely active and proportionally large brains, that are capable of electroperception and electrical communication with one another.
	- Because of the extreme energy consumption of their brains, they rely on very high-energy food and as such are particularly susceptible to the effects of climate change on their local ecosystems.
	- Since they represent an extreme edge case in vertebrate cognition, both in terms of nervous system structure, spatial navigation and communicative ability, further study of them is essential.
	- In order to facilitate further research, we need to understand the threat posed to them by anthropogenic climate change, and take measures to protect them from it.
	- Thesis
		- Further study of Mormyrids is essential for the study of vertebrate cognition, due to their unique neural anatomy, and we need to document and mitigate the effects of anthropogenic climate change on them to facilitate their study.
- Body paragraphs
	- Mormyrid brains
		- The brains of Mormyrids are notable due to their uniquely high relative oxygen consumption rate - more than 3 times higher than that of the next highest, humans -, and their very large cerebellums (gigantocerebellums). 
	- Electrical communication
		- Mormyrids use their electric organs and receptors to communicate with eachother in a manner that resembles human communication, enabling them to exchange information much more precisely and reliably than most other animals.
	- Research efforts
		- Research into mormyrid language has fallen behind research into the language of other species with complex languges such as dolphins, and many of the modern techniques for language analysis used in those other studies have yet to be tried on mormyrids. 
	- Ecological niche and role
		- In order to facilitate their advanced cognition, mormyrids require very energy-dense nutrition sources, which they are able to locate more reliably due to their spatial electroperception and cognitive abilities. 
	- Threats from climate change
		- Because of the extreme oxygen and calorie requirements of mormyrids, relatively mild changes to their ecosystems could cause their populations to rapidly collapse.
- Conclusion
	- Many new cross-discipline methods for analyzing animal language have arisen from adjacent studies, and the application of these techniques to mormyrids would be invaluable to the field of animal cognition.
	- Because their electrical emissions are vastly different in captivity compared to in their natural habitat, we need to take measures to understand and mitigate the effects of anthropogenic climate change on those natural habitats.
